The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is well developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long to get there.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed it by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that a paradoxical situation will be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, also said that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a remarkable drop in prices to which classical operators should also react.
At the same time, even before the entrance of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard here and there.
It has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be successful.
In other words, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we inform you about the debut of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Just after half a year, this operator got more than 100,000 customers and became the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, following Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more target groups.
In addition, in order for them to work effectively, it is enough for many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that, however, are often countered with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half the cheap with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a no trivial goal group.
This operator is addressed specifically to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and who he can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works on this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether it seems like a concept like that of Poland could hook up in our country.
He doubts Vodafone's spokesman, Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be a virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic does not seem too hopeful.
Rather it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," said mobile phone conversation, Jana Studničková, spokesman for the financial group Penta.
Indirectly, he assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not leaning on this idea.
Rather, they try to do their best to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in the meetings," said the group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then, maybe they'll spark better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At present we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2's opinion, adds: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
He adds: "In the network of T-Mobile it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some specific contract that could be studied on such short horizons."
Vodafone is more concerned with meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of sharing costs and infrastructure.
Precisely we consider it as the greatest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is found in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with the operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decline in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon came up.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by T-Mobile society.
It attests to the accessible public information on the ČTU website.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, it was not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Litigations (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile phone operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was more than interesting enough for classical operators," he added to our question Kristián Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that should represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that, they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators work normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile phone services"
Of course, the pressure on market media to function properly and lower prices do not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
The dramatic shock in all of this lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is a work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore have a corresponding rise in their market share of responsibility.
The tools needed to open up the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, lack, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added.
Interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú whereby telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial bidding a single market.
In this type of market, of course none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a specific segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are soaringly ascending.
Current complaints from stakeholders (indicted by GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which ÚOHS washes hands in all this matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act for the extension of ČTÚ's competition in the field of commercial tenders was tabled recently, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known by the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one watches.
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists on Czech mobile networks is unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile services which, however, only part of them are public.
They are usually companies that engage in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally, only a few of those elected get the list of prices for these companies.
The magic is in that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same by loading a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions in all Czech mobile telephone operators prohibit such a resale.
"If cases such as those quoted above were discovered, there could be talk of breach of contract conditions that could result in the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová answered the question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned can come to be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they obtain a not negligible profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a disparaging so much as a percentage of customers.
These, moreover, must accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of operators."
Precisely this is what it should look like to ČTÚ minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile phone operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this history and that its trading conditions do not permit it.
When we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves more or less from this failure.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened, and in none of the cases they have defended the operators but their customers.
Either with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to get the first virtual operator to appear and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Organ of Regulation all of this happens as if it were a burning nail.
By our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the powers in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this information between backstage is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators allow any virtual mobile phone operator to enter, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
