The MHD in Prague takes us Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, it is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company the date when the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at the moment by almost 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day bonus and the annual (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card in the info centers and posts of the transport company at the stations of the Metro, Muzeum, Městek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can be bought from yesterday on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket sales positions at subway stations, where until now they have to regularly queue to get a regular ticket out.
The bonus is purchased on the internet, and the Opencard card is recharged to you in one of the thirteen subsidiaries of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the disposal of the passengers a window with prepared staff that helps interested people with the purchase on the internet and also with the reloading of the voucher purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus in the Opencard on the vending machines found in some subway vestibules.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, remind us of a banknote pickup machine and travelers will probably have already set themselves at the stations of the Roztyly Metro, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start to work tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter into it the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will be loaded only into it.
The electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, on the circular trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of central Bohemian towns.
"On the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the area of the bonus," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization that establishes the timetables of the collective transport of Prague.
Circulation buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver's locker.
Upon entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Fund.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal said.
Passengers who do not travel on buses and do not remember when the validity of the bonus is finished can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be presented with the information about the validity of your document.
