We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it does not have treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or shows that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children and having a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will encourage the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the dreams come out try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the usual thing), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him to sound him information.
You won't get anything, because being asleep is not conscious of how to organize your thinking.
