The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating his 10th anniversary yesterday of his foundation, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has been once again one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had seriously been vacillated by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and the discontent of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gelineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec started his activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, he recalls Decary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence, " he says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in the successive Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary recalls, however, that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle since its inception on 28 September 1998.
At that time, we were in Europe at the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Decary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports by Krever and Gelineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied had no meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique of detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests allowing the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not antibodies against the virus, which were based on the tests used so far.
Nucleid acid tests allowed for shortening the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes every year between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products, more than 24 years will pass before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I think you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without any worries," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Island of the Meeting, which, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant ", Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec should also provide for sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Because more aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet injection.
Ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which regroups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, may give blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people proposing their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since the present life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood, "it afflicts Francine Decary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench of our thousandth blood sample from the umbilical cord and it is expected to draw more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this cordon blood-taking program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this ", since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
