Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion US dollars plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control on the part of the electors of their implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money invested, new arrangements to contain the number of stalled houses the lack of payment, as well as a right of control over wages paid to the leaders of the aided companies.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We make great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions about the daily lives of Americans will be immense," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would cause a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last hour they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who were late in the negotiations, were more favourable to the agreement, but did not forget to express their discontent with being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has been given certain arrangements to reach the agreement, particularly that would allow owners to keep their homes and that on the salary of the leaders of state-owned companies.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another chain to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it."
"The important points that I have read [show] is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said that the option of not doing anything is not acceptable."
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with the taxpayers' money the doubtful debts, the riskable and unsoldable assets of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the sinking of risk mortgage credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and to cause a freezing of liquidity and a ban on banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have emerged from the stagnation since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
With the aim of cutting the roughness for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to take up losses for five years with this program, it could impose new rates that would help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to be added 100 other billion if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
In return for its aid, Washington will obtain shares in the aided companies which will be worth dividends in case of profits and which will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the embargo procedures relating to housing obtained from real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote of the House of Representatives since today and that of the Senate next Wednesday.
