Overlay psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and, in the meantime, was examined through the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (FMRI) the active areas of the brain of the individuals participating in the experiment.
In both games they could earn money the participants , but during auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "auto prize" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members gambled.
In addition to this, another group was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction, the group members lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the auction phenomena only with the joy of winning and the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world, some 5 billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
An estimated 100,000 people are infected in this country, but only 7,000 are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are propagated by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with contaminated water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body humors (sperm, vaginal mood, saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be protected by A and B vaccine, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after eating the infected food, manifests by a general ill state, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear in the skin and in the white of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Every year a million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent slowly destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor by experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus of the body, thus it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
30 September is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic infections of the liver caused by viruses and to the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to a recent investigation, religious faith has a soothing effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
The Oxford University scientists conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - the British Telegraph newspaper reported.
Within the framework of this singular experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same amount of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was found that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first of the research series in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows: they fixed a glassy instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrat of the 17th century; and the Lady of the Armor of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers were hoping that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing religious painting or the other.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their hearts peace reigned."
As they observed the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases of truth change our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have for the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown by Madonna de Leonardo or by another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
