Smart car imitates bee flight
What would be the best method for developing technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the sensors of obstacles existing in nature?
For example, that of the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the beekeepers provided the starting point for the Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic car management system BR23C imitator of nature, to which they gave the characteristics of the beekeepers, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bee creates its own private oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety guard capsule - explained in the exposure Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The eyes composed of the bees play an important role, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the bees, modifies the direction by turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any existing system at present, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety guard capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process must be carried out in an opening and closing of the eyes.
However, unlike beekeepers, the movement cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of turning wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beekeepers to dodge other beekeepers, here they only used rotational motion and acceleration as a possibility for the auto robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is greater, which means they have longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction and not data processing capacity, no less storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes, no megabytes.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan's calculations, will be able to be incorporated into the standard manufactured models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles on his way.
