Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared with those of July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared with those of the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum extent, with 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The highest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to the monthly increase of 4.6 per cent in bags and belts and a 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9%), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within internal trade, a 0.3 per cent increase was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, a 13.2 per cent increase was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, with a determining weight, there was an 11 per cent increase.
Price decrease was recorded in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2%.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, with no change in energy and intermediate sector prices compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods producing branches, a decrease of 6.8 per cent was recorded and in the investment goods 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry calculated at HUF increased by 1.1 percent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
