Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, and France is the host of the European Union, who is also President of the European Union this year.
Mr Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fides, in his message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to the segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Roma children and is also the greatest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights organisations attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz Group of Deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies are left out of the labour market primarily because of their low level of schooling.
"Most young Gypsies have not finished middle school and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part of them can obtain university diplomas."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a crucial role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in teaching Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Member of the European Parliament, these issues need to be made widely aware both of the Roma and of non-Gypsies.
For the sooner the school begins a Gypsy student, the more possibilities you will have to become an active member of the labour market; through taxes on income and consumption they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, have to be guaranteed the right to quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Livia Járóka.
According to the European Parliament, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up the processes of school segregation immediately, which is why it is essential to ensure that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly complied with.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be offered the possibility that democratic space guarantees so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," said Járóka.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised annually since the Berlin meeting last year, held in the sign of the European Year of Equal Opportunities, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
