"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effective what is happening in the big Italian urban centers and also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory,"is as if a friend died, a acquaintance who shared a piece of space and so much excitement," notes the director of the new cinema Paradise, the film that twenty years ago I win the cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize at Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that may have been lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of the merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay most of them are the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these three Italian regions are themselves that have recorded the largest number of new meticos cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is ethically and morally embarrassing that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year."
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala be in the historical center that in the periphery.
The rules provided for include a means of tax facilitation for managers and advantages to the public in terms of mobility: spectators may enter the restricted traffic zone and have special parking charges.
"It's an initiative that I like" notes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by putting other measures in place.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of the meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because today the public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closure of the cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to realize the "New cinema Paradise", which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or Quirinale of already closed National Way, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side”.
